The paper deals with the design and implementation of a framework for programming adaptive distributed applications, which involves multiple participants interacting with each other. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category. The paper also discusses the use of a language called Adaptive Interaction-Oriented Choreography (AIOC) for programming these applications, which could place it in the Software Engineering (cs.SE) category. Additionally, the paper mentions the automatic generation of executable code for each participant, which could suggest a focus on Programming Languages (cs.PL). The paper also discusses the use of labelled transition system semantics for proving correctness, which could place it in the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category. Finally, the paper discusses the proof of deadlock freedom as a corollary, which could suggest a focus on Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO).
